But the amount of love and affection I have been shown wherever I have been this year, B1$ A lot depends on the body, I have 6-7 months to decide. My eyes were full of water and I just stood there in the dugout for a while. I realised I want to enjoy this. It was the same thing in Chennai, it was my last game over there but B3$ They love me for what I am. The kind of cricket I play, I think everyone in the stadium thinks they can play that way because there is nothing orthodox about it. So I feel they can relate to me more than anyone else. I don't want to change myself, I never wanted to portray myself in a way which I am not. I just keep it simple. Every trophy is special, but what is special about IPL is every crunch game you need to be ready. That's something we have done, there were lapses today, the bowling department didn't work, but it was the batting department that took the pressure off them today. I do get frustrated, it is human but I try to step into their shoes, every individual deals with pressure differently. Ajinkya and a few others are experienced, so you don't worry a lot about them. If anyone is confused, then can always ask. The special thing about Rayudu is he will always give his 100% when he is on his field. But with him in the team, I will never win the Fairplay Award. He always wants to contribute and he has been a fantastic cricketer. I've been playing with him for a long time, since the India A tours. He's a player who can play spin and pace equally well. It is something really special. I felt he would do something really special, I'm really happy for him. This game will be one he will remember, he's also like me - not someone who uses the phone often. What's important is that he has had a fantastic career and I hope he enjoys the next phase of his life...

commText: B0$ It is 1:36 in the morning, we've had to play this game over three days but it still went down to the very last ball of the competition. And now we can say it again - B1$ A chase that was truncated down to 15 overs, got off to a solid start with their openers Ruturaj and Devon Conway getting them a top start once again. It was Conway who was the more aggressive, taking down Shami and Hardik in the powerplay. The introduction of Noor Ahmad got GT the wickets, as he dismissed both openers in the same over. It looked like the scoring rate would slow down, but out walked Ajinkya Rahane who smoked two classy sixes off Josh Little. He then got two boundaries against Rashid, while his partner Dube struggled to find his timing. Dube finally found his gear in the final Rashid Khan over, hitting him for two sixes and getting CSK back in the contest. Rayudu was the next CSK batter to be a hero, he was the only one to pick Mohit Sharma's slower ones and slam it over the boundary ropes. Rayudu fell and then Dhoni was out first ball. Mohit Sharma then delivered almost the perfect last over, nailing four yorkers but then Sir Jadeja decided he'll have the final laugh, finishing the game off with a six and a four to eternalize his place in CSK folklore. Over to the presentations now...

Mohit Sharma to Jadeja, B0$, CSK CHAMPIONS!! Can you believe it?? This was a low full toss on the pads, Jadeja with a wiggle inwards and just a gentle tickle to the left of short fine. Runs away for four, nobody could stop that. Jadeja runs to his captain, and then is off on a celebratory run around the stadium, his other CSK teammates try to catch up with him.... Scenes of sheer joy, all those in yellow celebrate, they breathe a sigh of relief. Chin up, Mohit Sharma. That was a top quality last over, but not to be his night...
Last ball, who's your money on? Hardik having a chat with Mohit again. The field stays the same

A drink comes out for Mohit. Hardik gives him a pep talk. This is the ball, this is the ball that could make GT champions again..

commText: B0$ GT would be extremely happy that they have scored 214 in a grand finale! Runs on board in such pressure games can always prove to be telling and the home side definitely have the upper hand heading into the break. It was very unlike CSK tonight as they missed catches and run out opportunities in numbers and that can turn out to be a big factor. Even the ground fielding from them was ordinary and they gave away some free runs. Chahar dropped Gill on 2, it was literally a dolly. After that, 30 runs came off the 3rd and 4th over combined. That gave GT the momentum they were searching for. Jadeja fumbled a relatively easy opportunity to run Saha out but did outfox Gill with a beauty in the same over. Saha went on to score a Fifty but the real game changer was Sudharsan tonight. He batted on a different level and kept finding the boundaries at will. He missed out on a ton but the young man did remarkably well. Pathirana finished strong but the damage was already done by then. The bowling was off the mark for CSK. Chasing a target over 200 in an IPL final is a mammoth task. Can CSK pull it off? The highest total that has been chased in an IPL final was 200 by KKR against Punjab in 2014. B0$ The players have arrived and are going through the warmups. Our correspondent, Aayush Puthran, is feeling optimistic about the prospects today. "The crowd is warming up, cheers Ravindra Jadeja on as he takes a few throwdowns along the boundary line, warming up with the bat."

A packed crowd and millions watching were left frustrated as rain played spoilsport yesterday. But it's set to be another full-house in Ahmedabad despite the difficulties faced by the fans. Speaking of yesterday, Ambati Rayudu announced that this was going to be his last game.

B0$ It feels good the way I have batted this season. I had also said at the beginning that playing the entire domestic season for Mumbai this year helped me a lot. After that, the CSK management had told me what my role will be and they gave me the freedom to bat according to my game plan without any interference. The environment in the team is really good, the main thing is the management and the captain keep their faith in all the players. That also gives a lot of confidence to a player having the backing of the captain and the management. It is important for a cricketer to stay in the moment, there was a preparation for yesterday but the weather is not in our control. As a cricketer when you play Test cricket, the way you prepare and go through the processes, the same you can apply for these kind of situations as well.

B0$ (Dealing with rain delays) Neither is it easy, nor is it difficult. We were all pumped and mentally ready for yesterday, I felt like mentally we already played the match because you keep visualizing the game. It was mentally exhausting yesterday, but physically we are fine so hopefully we can play it like just another match and get over the line. (On having individual targets) I don’t have targets, but not in terms of how many runs I want to score. The target is according to the game situation, how I’m expected to bat and where can I score runs. I play in the moment, what’s best for that particular moment. The target is never scoring 600 or 800 runs. (On how he prepares) Some preparation is based on how you as a batter think the wicket will play, but once you are out there then you reassess and play accordingly. (On his family being in the stands) I’m happy to see that my family has come to watch the match, that neither reduces or increases the pressure. But the good moments are even better when there is family around.

B0$ The pitch is in the centre of the square. 66 meter square boundaries each side, and 74 meters down the ground. Slight changes today in the atmospheric conditions - it's cooler this evening. I think that's going to help the ball swing around a little bit. Has much changed from yesterday? Not really. If anything, remember last night we had those grass clippings that were rolled in. Maybe they've been removed a little bit which could bring in the slow pace bowlers, especially on a good length where guys like Mohit hit it hard, take the pace off. And of course we've got the quality spinners from both teams. I predict it's going to be around 180 (par score). Whatever happens though, you have to have a bat, particularly CSK.

commText: B0$ No batter other than Shubman Gill has stamped his authority. Sai Sudharsan has been impressive in the few opportunities he has got but the other batters have struggled a bit. No batter other than Gill is in the list of top 20 batters in this season. The fact that Hardik is second in the run scorer’s list and has scored 325 runs in total, shows you that Gill has been on a different level. Their designated finishers, Miller and Tewatia, have had less game time and if the CSK bowlers manage to dismantle GT’s top order quickly, it will be a stern test for them. The pressure of a finale can make even the best susceptible.

B0$ A team which boasts of both the orange cup and purple cap holder is meant to be dominant. Shubman Gill (orange cap) has scored 3 tons in his last 4 games and has accumulated 851 runs so far in this season – tells you the young man has taken the stage by storm. Also, Mohit Sharma's resurgence from a net bowler for GT previous season to a bowler who is picking up wickets in abundance now is nothing short of a fairy tale! When it comes to incisiveness in the bowling department, they have arguably the most potent and reliable bowling attack at their disposal. Shami (purple cap) swings the ball like a banana in the powerplay, Rashid and Noor choke the batters in the middle overs by weaving their magic, and Mohit makes the opposition dance to the tune of his variations in the death overs. GT has the three highest wicket-takers this season – Shami (28), Rashid (27), and Mohit (24). The defending champions are in great rhythm and would be hungry to win back-to-back trophies. Only twice in the history of IPL has a team won the trophy twice in a row, Chennai Super Kings in 2010 and 2011 and Mumbai Indians in 2019 and 2020.

B0$ A team that finished second after the league stages and then made it straight to the final generally don’t have too many weaknesses. However, the success of their top-order has meant the middle order has had very little batting. The likes of Moeen Ali, Ambati Rayudu and even Dhoni have had very little to do this season, and a final would be a bad time for this franchise to lose 2-3 quick wickets. Secondly, barring Deepak Chahar and Jadeja, none of their bowlers have played an IPL final, or even a game of this magnitude. So how will they hold up to more than a lakh spectators jeering them up will be interesting to see…
